activities.message:
Hi @geeknik 

Thanks for submitting this report. I'm having some doubts on whether this issue is valid. I think this is a false positive reported by AddressSanitizer, I'll explain below why. When I try to reproduce your report I'm just getting a "INVALID ALGORITHM" error after which the application exits. I don't see any crash happening, which is likely to be expected in this case.

Also looking purely as the source code I'm having some doubts:

cmdgen.c, lines 813-821:
```c
                    if (alg)
                        bits = ssh_key_public_bits(
                            alg, ptrlen_from_strbuf(ssh2blob));
                    else
                        bits = -1;
                } else {
 >>                 strbuf_free(ssh2blob);      // AddressSanitizer triggers on this "free" 
                }
                sfree(ssh2alg);
```

cmdgen.c, lines 972-983:
```c

                if (!ssh2blob) {
                    assert(ssh2key);
                    ssh2blob = strbuf_new();
                    ssh_key_public_blob(ssh2key->key, BinarySink_UPCAST(ssh2blob));
                }

                ssh2_write_pubkey(fp, ssh2key ? ssh2key->comment : origcomment,
  >>                              ssh2blob->s, ssh2blob->len,   // AddressSanitizer "use after free"
                                  (outtype == PUBLIC ?
                                   SSH_KEYTYPE_SSH2_PUBLIC_RFC4716 :
                                   SSH_KEYTYPE_SSH2_PUBLIC_OPENSSH));
            }
```

So AddressSanitizer reports a "use-after-free" on line 979. However if you look up a few lines you'll see that the buffer is allocated again if it was clear before: ```sh2blob = strbuf_new();```.

@lasagna
